<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Hindu_calendar_1871-72.jpg" class="image" title="A page from the Hindu calendar 1871-72."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Hindu_calendar_1871-72.jpg/250px-Hindu_calendar_1871-72.jpg" width="250" height="676" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Hindu_calendar_1871-72.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
A page from the Hindu calendar 1871-72.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>Hindu calendar</b> used in ancient times has undergone many changes in the process of regionalization, and today there are several regional <b>Indian <a href="/wiki/Calendar" title="Calendar">calendars</a></b>, as well as an <a href="/wiki/Indian_national_calendar" title="Indian national calendar">Indian national calendar</a>.</p>
<p>Most of these calendars are inherited from a system first enunciated in <i><a href="/wiki/Vedanga_Jyotisha" title="Vedanga Jyotisha">Vedanga Jyotisha</a></i> of Lagadha, a late BCE adjunct to the <a href="/wiki/Vedas" title="Vedas">Vedas</a>, standardized in the <i><a href="/wiki/Surya_Siddhanta" title="Surya Siddhanta">Surya Siddhanta</a></i> (3rd century CE) and subsequently reformed by astronomers such as <a href="/wiki/Aryabhata" title="Aryabhata">Aryabhata</a> (499 CE), <a href="/wiki/Varahamihira" title="Varahamihira">Varahamihira</a> (6th c. CE), and <a href="/wiki/Bhaskara" title="Bhaskara" class="mw-redirect">Bhaskara</a> (12th c. CE). There are differences and regional variations abound in these computations, but the following is a general overview of Hindu lunisolar calendar.</p>
